The '''Channel Tunnel''' ({{lang-fr|Le tunnel sous la Manche}}), (also referred to as the '''Chunnel''')&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|title=Oxford Dictionary of English|publisher=[[OUP]] Oxford|edition=2nd Edition Revised|date=11 August 2005|isbn=3411021446}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
 | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2009/dec/20/world/la-fg-chunnel20-2009dec20
 | title = Rail passengers spend a cold, dark night stranded in Chunnel
 | date = 20 December 2009
 | author=Janet Stobart
 | publisher=L.A. Times
 | accessdate = 27 June 2010
}}&lt;/ref&gt; is a {{convert|50.5|km|mi|adj=on}} undersea rail [[tunnel]] linking [[Folkestone, Kent|Folkestone]], [[Kent]] in England with [[Coquelles]], [[Pas-de-Calais]] near [[Calais]] in northern France beneath the [[English Channel]] at the [[Strait of Dover]]. At its lowest point, it is {{convert|75|m|ft|sigfig=2}} deep.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url = http://www.raileurope.com/us/rail/eurostar/channel_tunnel.htm | title = The Channel Tunnel | publisher=raileurope.com | accessdate = 19 July 2009 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;ICE p. 95&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;autogenerated1&quot;&gt;{{cite web | url = http://www.popularmechanics.com/science/extreme_machines/4217338.html?series=23 | title = Turkey Building the World's Deepest Immersed Tube Tunnel | publisher=[[Popular Mechanics]] | accessdate = 19 July 2009 }}&lt;/ref&gt; At {{convert|37.9|km}}, the Channel Tunnel possesses the longest undersea portion of any tunnel in the world, although the [[Seikan Tunnel]] in Japan is both longer overall at {{convert|53.85|km}}, and deeper at {{convert|240|m}} below sea level.

The tunnel carries high-speed [[Eurostar]] passenger trains, [[Eurotunnel Shuttle]] [[roll-on/roll-off]] vehicle transport—the largest in the world—and international rail [[freight train]]s.&lt;ref name=&quot;Chisholm&quot; /&gt; The tunnel connects end-to-end with the [[LGV Nord]] and [[High Speed 1]] high-speed railway lines. In 1996 the [[American Society of Civil Engineers]] identified the tunnel as one of the [[American Society of Civil Engineers#World Wonders|Seven Wonders of the Modern World]].&lt;ref name=&quot;The Plain Dealer&quot; /&gt;

Ideas for a cross-Channel fixed link appeared as early as 1802,&lt;ref name=&quot;Whiteside p17&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{ cite news | url = http://library.thinkquest.org/5983/pages/chunnel.htm | title = The Channel Tunnel | publisher=library.thinkquest.org | accessdate = 19 July 2009 }}&lt;/ref&gt; but British political and press pressure over compromised national security stalled attempts to construct a tunnel.&lt;ref name=&quot;Wilson pp. 14–21&quot; /&gt; However, the eventual successful [[megaproject|project]], organised by [[Eurotunnel]], began construction in 1988 and opened in 1994. The project came in 80% over its predicted budget.&lt;ref name=&quot;Flyvbjerg p. 12&quot; /&gt; Since its construction, the tunnel has faced several problems. Fires have disrupted operation of the tunnel. Illegal immigrants and asylum seekers have attempted to use the tunnel to enter England,&lt;ref&gt;{{ cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/kent/7171985.stm | title = Four men caught in Channel Tunnel | publisher=BBC News | accessdate = 19 July 2009 | date = 4 January 2008 }}&lt;/ref&gt; causing a minor diplomatic disagreement over the siting of the [[Sangatte]] [[refugee camp]], which was eventually closed in 2002.&lt;ref&gt;{{ cite news | url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2002/may/23/immigration.immigrationandpublicservices1 | title = Sangatte refugee camp |work=The Guardian |location=UK | accessdate = 19 July 2009} }}&lt;/ref&gt;

