  <page>
    <title>Cutaway (filmmaking)</title>
    <id>5719</id>
    <revision>
      <id>431109845</id>
      <timestamp>2011-05-27T01:48:33Z</timestamp>
      <contributor>
        <ip>70.160.232.12</ip>
      </contributor>
      <comment>/* Usage */</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">In [[film]], a '''cutaway''' is the interruption of a continuously filmed action by inserting a view of something else.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Glossary|publisher=The Art of the Guillotine|date=|url=http://www.artoftheguillotine.com/glossaryc.html|accessdate=31 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; It is usually, although not always, followed by a cut back to the first shot, when the cutaway avoids a [[jump cut]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Videography glossary|publisher=Calgary Board of Education|date=|url=http://schools.cbe.ab.ca/b690/Curriculum/computerop/comp9plus/CTS901-03/CTS9Plus-VideoGlossary.html|accessdate=30 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Method==
Cutaways do not have to contribute any dramatic content of their own, often being used to help the [[Film editing|editor]] assemble a longer sequence.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Cutaway|publisher=MediaCollege.com|date=|url=http://www.mediacollege.com/video/shots/cutaway.html|accessdate=31 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; For this reason, editors choose cutaways related to the main action, such as another action or object in the same location.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Module 51|publisher=Cybercollege.com|date=|url=http://www.cybercollege.com/tvp051.htm|accessdate=31 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; For example, if the main shot is of a man walking down an alley, possible cutaways may include a shot of a cat on a nearby dumpster or a shot of a woman watching from a window overhead.

==Usage==
Its most common uses in dramatic films are to adjust the pace of the main action, to conceal the deletion of some unwanted part of the main shot, or to allow the joining of parts of two versions of that shot.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=The 'Grammar' of Television and Film|publisher=Aberystwyth University|date=|url=http://www.aber.ac.uk/media/Documents/short/gramtv.html|accessdate=31 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; For example, a scene may be improved by cutting a few [[Film frame|frames]] out of an actor's pause; a brief view of a listener can help conceal the break. Or the actor may fumble some of his lines in a group shot; rather than discarding a good version of the shot, the director may just have the actor repeat the lines &quot;in one&quot; and cut to that solitary view when necessary.

Cutaways are also used often in older horror films in place of special effects. For example, a shot of a zombie getting its head cut off may, for instance, start with a view of an axe being swung through the air, followed by a close-up of the actor swinging it, then followed by a cut back to the now severed head. [[George A. Romero]], creator of the [[Living Dead#Romero's Dead series|Dead Series]], and [[Tom Savini]] pioneered effects that removed the need for cutaways in horror films.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=George Romero Surveys the Dead|publisher=Parallax view|date=|url=http://parallax-view.org/2008/10/29/george-romero-roams-the-land-of-the-dead/|accessdate=31 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Tom Savini biography|publisher=film reference|date=|url=http://www.filmreference.com/Writers-and-Production-Artists-Ro-She/Savini-Tom.html|accessdate=31 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In [[news broadcasting]] and [[Documentary film|documentary work]], the cutaway is used much as it would be in fiction. On location, there is usually just one camera to film an interview, and it's usually trained on the interviewee. Often there is also only one microphone. After the interview, the interviewer will usually repeat his questions while he himself is being filmed, with pauses as they act as if to listen to the answers. These shots can be used as cutaways. Cutaways to the interviewer, called '''[[noddies]]''', can also be used to cover cuts.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Talk about Newsnight|publisher=The BBC|date=|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/newsnight/2007/08/faking_it.html|accessdate=31 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Some television shows utilized cutaways, mostly in comedies, where they're often known as 'cutaway [[gag (joke)|gags]]'. Some of the first to do so were ''[[The Simpsons]]'' and ''[[The Critic]]''. ''[[Family Guy]]'' has frequently used them for visual gags since premiering on television, and characters sometimes mention the use of the technique. ''[[Family Guy]]'' having popularized the cutaway gag, it now can be found in a wide range of television shows, from animated comedies like ''[[Drawn Together]]'' to [[live-action]] comedies like ''[[30 Rock]]'', ''[[Titus (TV series)]]'' (cancelled), ''[[Malcolm in the Middle]]'' (cancelled), ''[[Arrested Development]]'' (cancelled) and ''[[Scrubs]]'' (also cancelled).

